author: CosmoWenman

description.text:
Our robots use loads of sensors. Sensors of all types! But how to attach a variety of sensors to the robot easily? How to make it adjustable? This sensor mount was born out of that need. A simple, three piece adjustable sensor mount(two 'ends' and a 'middle') that is assembled with two bolts was just what the robo doctor ordered. Currently this bracket can be printed in different lengths using different mid parts. bracket_mid_5cm results in a ~5cm long bracket
bracket_mid results in a ~9cm long bracket
bracket_mid_15 results in a ~15cm long bracket bracket_wide is a wider end piece to be used instead of the bracket_base piece in order to mount a wider variety of sensors to the end. //////// UPDATES /////////
4/1/14 - Increased depth of bracket_wide to increase stiffness, increased surface area slightly to prevent gaps when printing on lower settings.

Print two of the bracket_base pieces. One is for attaching the mount to the surface and the other is used to mount sensors.   
Print a single bracket_mid piece.  
The bracket end pieces can be bolted to the bracket mid part using two small bolts and nuts.

title: Printed bevel gear for steering gear for BIG loader (Traktor)

description.text:
Replacement bevel gear for the steering gear for our BIG loader (toy Traktor).  
The original gear had become loose. Factory-side, it was only pressed onto the steering rod. As the original gear was made out of nylon/PA or POM, adhesive was not really a viable option.  
This printed replacement gear has a nut trap for M3 nut and can therefore be easily and securely fitted onto the steering rod.

Printed in PLA 3mm on my reprap printer with a 0.5mm nozzle.  
You might want to tweak the nut trap settings, mine was a tight fit.  
For mounting, I first removed the steering wheel and then removed the steering rod from below. Then, I pressed the new gear onto the rod and secured it with an M3 screw. After reinserting the rod, the steering wheel was mounted.

title: Mini Heavy Duty Printable Filament Spool

description.text: UPDATE Shorter arms, longer holder so that it comes out to the right proportion on the back of the replicator. Old file versions not kept. if you've already downloaded them delete and redownload before printing. UPDATE2 Additional holder options, even shorter arms and spool ends that won't pop out under the slightest presuure. These changes are untested as of time of publishing because I've made hack fixes that I hope no one else has to. Old Zip file deleted. New zip file is latest and greatest with no extras. Should be all you need. This is a lot of little modificaitons on a lot of people's designs that I'm putting together in once place so one one else has to make a lot of little modification on a lot of people's designs. Be sure to check out the ancestor list for a full history.

Sing along everybody! Oohhhh!
The *holder-x1.stl is connected to the ReplicatorMountx1.stl,
The ReplicatorMount-x1.stl is connected to the SpoolHub-x1.stl,
The SpoolHub-x1.stl is connected to the SpoolArm2-x3.stls,
The SpoolArm2-x3.stls are connected to the SpoolEnds2-x3.stls,
Oh hear the word of the Lord. Use the BackHolder-x1 if you want to mount your spool in the traditional place. There are many options of SideHolders. Check carefully to decide which ones you want to use. Use /thing:26747 if you mount it on the side. When you put the ReplicatorMount-x1 into the *Holder-x1 you will want to put it away from where it clips in. It may seem like that's too far over and imbalanced but it's necessary so the arms have room to rotate.
The ReplicatorMount-x1 is tapered so it slips in easily but gets tight at the end. Give it a good shove and it'll hold fast. You'll have to angle the SpoolEnd2-x3s into the SpoolArm2-x3s. This is so they'll hold themselves in place, but you may still wish to glue them in.

comments.text: Glad that they are going together for you. They weren't that tight a fit for me. The reason you may be getting a tighter print may be that your filament diameter is too low so you are laying down too much plastic. Fixing this can be a difference of 2 tenth of a millimeter, the difference between a snug fit and needing a vice. Getting filament diameter right was the first thing I learned and it's served me well as a silver bullet.

title: Shadowblade heavy tank for small printer

description.text:
This was a combination of three different file sets, with some bits added.

I got the tracks and hull from here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1359137

I got the gun and shadowsword "turret" from here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2626280

And I stole some details from here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:582511

All the turrets move and pivot. The lascannons are from Cadian heavy weapon teams, and there are some other Cadian bits added.

I printed this on a Monoprice Mini Select V2 over the course of a few days. Some of the files have smaller parts repeated because they either didn't print correctly how they where arranged on my printer, or had to be redone for some reason.

The pivots for the lascanon turrets are really tight, I recommend sizing the pivot part at 95% to fit the hole on the turret better. The turret for the heavy bolter is just a lascannon turret printed at 105% to fit the quad heavy bolters.

I sanded this with a metal file, 220 grit sandpaper, and I applied Bondo filler and sanded again.

Here is my Imgur gallery of the completed tank after priming.
https://imgur.com/a/c4X0j

Edit 11/23/2017: I realized I forgot to include the rear armor plates I attached the fuel barrels to, so I added them.

title: Companion Cube Speaker Box or a detailed model of a companion cube

description.text:
This was initially done as an exemplar for my students, but I thought I would share it with the whole world.
For fans of Portal/Portal 2, this is intended to be a speaker box designed around the Companion Cube. The circuit kit for the speaker is not my own design but can be purchased from here http://www.designability.com.au/classroom-projects/stereo-ipod-dock and has evenything in the kit you need, minus the solder, soldering iron and music source.
The base cube is a 100mm cube.
All files for building this are supplied and the name of the file indicates the part name, the colour I used and the number of prints of the file required, e.g. Knob-White_1 means it is the volume knob, white material, 1 print required.
The PCB can be held in place by the nut on the potentiometer (volume control) and there are supports for this inside the box.
Speakers are held in by contact glue as are the white parts glued to the grey box.
Part “Heart-White_6” may need to be scaled down to 98% depending on the tolerances of your printer as I found it to be a tough fit in the hole on the outside of the box or just trim with a craft knife. I used a Flashforge Guider 2 to print my version.
On the other hand, if you choose to print this and use it for nothing more than it being a cool model of a companion cube, go right ahead.
Enjoy!
If there are any problems, recommendations, requests, etc, please feel free to let me know and I can re-upload.
I will also shortly be uploading the pattern for the standard box students use which is laser cut 3mm acrylic; same circuit kit, just a bit quicker and cheaper to make.

I thought I would see how much an insulated head would effect the heating of my Taz5 Hexhead. I couldn't really tell much improvement in heating from room temp to 240C. I did notice about a 10 percent reduction in the rate of cooling. If you're pushing your extruder to the limit of it's ability to heat the filament then this could help you a little. Your performance may vary so give it a try.

Just wax the model of the head, paste wax or clear polish works well. This will help release the silicon. I just worked my way around the model putting a 2 to 3 mm coating. I had a little cup of Isopropyl Alcohol to dip my finger in to smooth out the applied silicon. I used J-B WELD Red Hi_Temp RTV on the final version but plain old clear silicon seem to handle the 240 degrees at least for a quick test.

After it sets up which can be over 24 hours you just need to trim it to fit on the model and slip it off. The pictures should explain the process well enough.

Cheers
Steve

description.text:
This is a 3D model of the Hurricane Katrina at its maximum intensity at 12:45pm CDT on Aug. 28, 2005. It was created by NASA by processing visible and thermal infrared images acquired from NOAA’s GOES 12 satellites. At that moment, Katrina was a Category 5 storm on the Saffir–Simpson hurricane wind scale (SSHWS), with the maximum winds of 175 mph (280 km/h).

This is a very easy model to print and it will look great on your desk. There are 2 sizes to choose from: large (195x195x21mm) and small (97x97x10mm).

If you would like to support the victims of the recent hurricanes Harvey, Irma, and Maria, please consider making a donation to Heart to Heart International (www.hearttoheart.org). You can also get a finished, cold-casted copy of this model from our etsy shop and we'll donate 10% of the sale price directly to Heart to Heart International.

Finished model available at: https://www.etsy.com/listing/573823809/category-5-hurricane

We hope that this beautiful model will become another wonderful item on your desk, shelf or stand, that will remind you of the beauty and power of mother nature. It may also spark a conversation about storm formation and the science behind this model. And finally it will be a beautiful reminder of how we can support each other by sharing and giving back.

Credits: The original 3D CAD model was created by Francis Reddy and made available by NASA under Creative Commons License.

title: Grove Temperature Sensor Case for Seed Studio - WIO Link

description.text:
This 3D model is a case for the Grove temperature and humidity sensor which works with Seed Studio's WIO Link product. It is a two part case that includes a base that the sensor can be screwed to with 3 small fasteners and a lid that snaps in place.

The lid has two rectangular holes to accommodate the sensor device on the PCB assembly and the cable connector. If I were to make any modifications to the model, I would adjust the rectangular hole in the lid to better accommodate the sensor.

This model has been printed on a Makerbot Replicator+ with PLA filament. A raft was used because it is recommended for the Replicator+. Other printers would not require a raft. 5% infill was used and that seemed to be adequate.

This case is a remix of the "Grove Sensor Mount - Large" model that was published by Ccirone2, on Mar 9, 2017.

author: dougmeixel

description.text:
PLEASE LET ME KNOW WHAT YOU THINK BY LIKING AND COMMENTING

We've all been there. You go on a skiing trip, and you don't enjoy it. Why? Because your thinking about your Teal Drone and wishing that it was there with you. That's all that you think about the entire time and you are miserable. I have decided to put an end to this issue that we have all experienced. Now your Teal Drone can ski side by side next to you. This design combines skis with looks, including a low-poly cover. What are you waiting for? Print this out and surprise your drone with a pair of skis.

comments.text: The legs seem a little on the short side, will they reach the ground?
comments.author: TuckyIA

comments.text: Also, many people may notice I have been commenting on several designs; no design can be perfect and I am trying to give feedback so that the designers of those covers can make them even better. I would be glad to see feedback on my designs, and while I'm sure no one would do this, please don't post rude comments anywhere. It doesn't contribute. I haven't seen any particularly rude comments yet. Though I don't know how many people will see this post - probably more than have seen some of my designs.
comments.author: TuckyIA

comments.text: Is there any particular reason you continue to post pictures showing other drones at the Teal Drone Challenge?
comments.author: MazeMieter

comments.text: That is simply a thumbnail. As I do not own a teal I can not show an image of it on the drone itself. I believe that an interesting thumbnail draws more attention than simply the file like many other designs.
